Load packages and data

library(tidyverse) 
library(datasauRus)
data("datasaurus_dozen")

Exercises

Exercise 1

The datasaurus_dozen dataset has 1846 rows and 3 columns (varaibles). The three variables are (1) dataset

Exercise 2

Plot the data in the dino dataset:

dino_data <- datasaurus_dozen %>%
  filter(dataset == "dino")

ggplot(data = dino_data, mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_point()

The scatterplot reveals that the datapoints form the shape of a dinosaur.

Calculate the correlation between x and y in this dataset:

dino_data %>%
  summarize(r = cor(x, y))
## # A tibble: 1  1
##         r
##     <dbl>
## 1 -0.0645

The Pearson correlation coefficient is approximately r = 0.064, which suggests a strongly weak negative linear relationship between x and y. This indicates that there is little to no linear relationship between x and y.

Exercise 3

Repeat the same analysis for star dataset.

star <- datasaurus_dozen %>% 
  filter(dataset == "star")

ggplot(data = star, mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) + 
  geom_point()

The scatterplot shows that the data points form a star shape.

star %>% 
  summarise(r = cor(x, y))
## # A tibble: 1  1
##         r
##     <dbl>
## 1 -0.0630

The correlation coefficient for the star dataset is approximately r = -0.063, which is similar to the dino datasets correlation of -0.064 and shows little to no linear relationship between x and y as well

Exercise 4

Repeat the same analysis for away dataset.

away <- datasaurus_dozen %>% 
  filter(dataset == "away")

ggplot(data = away, mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) + 
  geom_point()

The scatterplot shows a distinct pattern that is quite different from the dino and star shapes.

away %>%
  summarize(r = cor(x, y))
## # A tibble: 1  1
##         r
##     <dbl>
## 1 -0.0641

The Pearson correlation coefficient is approximately r = -0.064, which still indicates a strongly weak negative correlation between x and y.

Exercise 5

Visualize all 13 datasets at once and compare their correlation coefficients

ggplot(datasaurus_dozen, aes(x = x, y = y, color = dataset)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  facet_wrap(~dataset, ncol = 4) + 
  theme(legend.position = "none")

library(knitr)
datasaurus_dozen %>% 
  group_by(dataset) %>% 
  summarise(r = cor(x, y)) %>% 
  knitr::kable(digits = 3, caption = "Correlation between x and y for all datasets")
Correlation between x and y for all datasets
dataset r
away -0.064
bullseye -0.069
circle -0.068
dino -0.064
dots -0.060
h_lines -0.062
high_lines -0.069
slant_down -0.069
slant_up -0.069
star -0.063
v_lines -0.069
wide_lines -0.067
x_shape -0.066

As shown in the table above, all 13 datasets have a correlation coefficient very close to -0.06. Despite their drastically different visualization (dinos, stars, circles, etc.), they show similar relationship between x and y, which can be misleading on their own. This highlights the importance of data visualization and always visualizing data before analyzing it.
